\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This is hopeless!\u8221\'94 Pyetle yelled in between bursts of Mandri\u8217\'92s flame. \u8220\'93We need to\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94 another blast of fire annihilated a giant fly that shat out silk like a spider. \u8220\'93We need to run!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Run where?!\u8221\'94 Moto wailed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s iron bar unbuckled a ratbird\u8217\'92s ribs from its spine. \u8220\'93The tunnel!\u8221\'94 he roared.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri heard all this and cleared a path back to the constricting tunnel from which they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d come. If they could flee back into it, they would be surrounded by rock instead of angles of attack. But flailing tail and claw converged to fill the gap as soon as it was opened.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Wet pricked Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s cheek. He looked up and saw a scattering of raindrops glittering amongst the swarm of Sparks. He supposed that it was spit, a sad attempt meant to douse his fire, but no, the demons above were pissing in excitement. Only the shadows knew what other excretions rained down, for the smell of it was subsumed by the acrid fumes of burnt fur and flesh.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s iron bar snapped the stick-like leg of a giant stork, twice taller than himself. The flapping beast crashed down upon him. Its sharp beak whipped towards his chest, only to be stabbed through the gullet by Moto\u8217\'92s sword. The beast\u8217\'92s flailing wings smacked both men around. The resultant cloud of feathers obscured a herd of lion fanged goats who leaped, ten at once, hoping to overwhelm through strength of number.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s fire bowled them over, igniting their woolen coats. Those which still had legs, fled in distress. More unsightly beasts took their places.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I can\u8217\'92t!\u8221\'94 Mandri shouted in between gasps of fire, praying the others understood that he couldn\u8217\'92t save them, and protect himself, and clear a path for retreat, all while his Spark\u8217\'92s power surged in his ears and his head pulsed with a heat which threatened to split his skull. Such was swell behind his eyes that his vision bulged. Then he heard the stomp of something massive\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a stump-legged whale. He pivoted towards it, to blast it open, but something popped in his neck. Heat flared into the back of his jaw. He fell to his knees, struggled to breathe. He clawed at his throat, pressed it, squeezed it, but it was swollen tight. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 On came the demon horde. On came that impossible gray whale with its clean, heaving bulk so heavy it should have broken its bones. Mandri tried to summon his flame, but the moment he opened his mouth, that searing heat wrapped around his jaw and shut it. He loosed a panicked whine as his companions heaved against the press of beasts, all while that whale-thing gained momentum. Its thumping feet shook the ground as it stormed into a gallop, and finally, it leaped. Striped belly and all, it leaped into the air, confident of its majesty and blubber. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Ayram snarled and leaped right back at it like some mad harpooner. He met the beast in the air, crashed against its snout, tumbled along its table head, then whipped his spud-bar spear around to stab the great beast\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eye. They fell together.  Uncontrolled, the demonic whale hit the ground awkward and hard. Its long spine snapped. It\u8217\'92s skin snagged and ripped, spilling its entrails. After, there came a deafening, stupefying BOOM, followed by a CRACK.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The Black floor quaked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 For a moment, Mandri forgot his great pain amidst confusion, for while that whale was large, he did not think it was large enough to crack this solid of Black. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Then the floor quaked again.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Half the demon horde crashed into the other half, bleating and yelping. The Black quaked again, including walls and ceiling. Whole herds of climbing beasts were shaken loose. The rain of their bodies splashed onto the confused mass of demons below, and now the Black quaked again, a steady rumble easing into a great big BOOOOOM.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The entirety of floor shattered into islands. Clawing and slipping, thousands of demons fell into cracks and disappeared. Their shrieks took on an altogether different tone, higher pitched, more feral; screams of fright.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri scrambled nearer to the Hrkan Vessels. Together, they braced against the lift and tilt as the earthquake threatened to slide them down into a sudden abyss.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The rumbling settled., for the demon horde was suddenly fleeing. All the Sparks and all their lines of hunger were bending away from the central hole in the floor into which the Burshageet had fallen, and out of which Lora had flown. It looked now like a , a, for a geyser of liquid Black, thick as the hole itself, shot out with such force that the spray smashed into the ceiling. The backspray showered the rest of the room in viscous fluid. Mandri hid behind his arm, wondering what in the world was going on, when suddenly, a bright light illuminated the threads of his robe. He peeked over them and saw the geyser of liquid Black burst open, then evaporate in the light of a four pointed star, glowing white.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 This star was the size of a . It hovered in the air like a . Its pure, cleansing light painted the horde of demons as with a palette knife; stark and flattening whites, with hard and sharp lines and slashing shadows.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The star performed a quarter turn. At once, every single shrieking demon blinked out of existence.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The star performed another quarter-turn, and the entirety of the Black chasm surrounding Mandri and his companions shattered into splinters, yet stayed in place, calling to mind the glittering dome of the cosmos.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The star pulsed. A wave of white light washed over Mandri, tickling his headache, cooling his neck, calming his fear, pacifying him as though though this environ were a womb and he was being born again.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Solraheen!\u8221\'94 Pyetle praised as he fell to his knees, crying tears of amazement.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri himself was enraptured by disbelief. That star had risen out from under all this Black, and there was a bright intelligence hiding inside it, listening. What else could it be but the god of all creation, Solraheen?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tongue moved to shape a word, but for what purpose should he speak to a being composed of light? Should he thank it for deliverance?  Would it understand? It must, if it decided to spare him and his. Should he praise it, as Pyetle and his Vessels praised it? He shied away from this urge, for he\u8217\'92d always believed that an omniscience would have no use for his worship, or even desire, as it was, in itself, complete. And more, this was the god of creation, it had given him a voice and a mind. Why else would these gifts be given if not to express themselves in all their many colors? Let Pyetle worship.  But The urge to say something, anything, was interrupted when his own voice was channeled into his own head, loud and clear and demanding. This shining Spark of divinity wanted to know:}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 Where have you been?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Teeth set on edge, Mandri refused to answer, because if anyone must be made to answer for an absence it should be this god who abandoned His creation. And now, there was something he wanted to ask this star, if indeed it was Solraheen: Where have }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 you}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  been?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The star\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s center blinked. A pulse of light dazzled out, diffusing into rays of red, green, and blue. The clarity of these colors squeezed Mandri right out of his mind, compressing all his protestations into a tearful, whispered \u8220\'93Why?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The moment this \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91why?\u8217\'92 left his lips, it was peeled open. All the variegated forms of \u8216\'91why?\u8217\'92 spilled out:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Why make something instead of nothing?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Why invest the world with sickness, heartbreak, and death?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Why, and this was the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91why\u8217\'92 which spurred all spiritual anxiety, why do some live happy lives, while others suffer? Did the suffering disobey? Did they sin? Mandri knew he would be accused of playing the victim here, but he had seen the world, and in no meaningful sense could a starving babe disobey or sin. Against the vastness of all creation, he was little different.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The star picked these questions up and poked them into a neat bouquet. It handed them back. The incomprehensibility of this gesture slipped Mandri right past logic and into a revelation: his questions weren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t questions at all, but a set of statements imposing his own model of reality onto the world. As such, no one else but him could give an answer. And this revelation went down to a lower level, for all models of reality were only models, not reality itself, and so it wasn\u8217\'92t a matter of shifting over to some truer model; there would always be a \u8216\'91Why?\u8217\'92. And now he was at the deepest level, where understanding was laid bare as a model making tool which could only ever coarse grain the truth, and approximate, and draw lines where none existed. Understanding, here in the nude, was the same as ignorance.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Then he found the bottom:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 God was not capable of understanding.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 God had no need of understanding.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 God simply saw reality as it was.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Hidden inside that fallen star was no bright intelligence, but blank awareness. In it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s light, all suffering was geometrical, mere shapes in the causal flow.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri shut his eyes, and with eyes closed, this revelation seemed to him like nonsense. Cheap, cheap, nonsense. This could not be the fallen star named Solraheen, for no good god would try to convince him that understanding was equitable to ignorance. To say so was a corruption of mind. Understanding was understanding, ignorance was ignorance, and that bright star in front of him was Schisol.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A force pressed down upon him, spread evenly over all his skin. It pressed him flat against the ground, face down, prostrate, imbuing in him a well deserved humility.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Against his better judgment, Mandri surrendered. His mind went blank. He existed now in a state of pure ignorance. Nothing was communicated to him. There was only a grim sense that he was deluded, that the revelation he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d just had was a farce. He was a bundle of feelings and that was all. Understanding? This was not a model making tool, but a mere feeling, completely disconnected to whether or not something was true.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 What happened next, language could not bear. It went that the star plucked him, smelled him, delighted in him, radiated joy, and then cast him aside like a wildflower.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Night turned into midnight.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 He awoke to find himself laying on a disk of Black at the bottom of a crater, high in the Goree mountains. He was not surprised to find himself sitting in the crater\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s, but he was surprised to see the blue and chilling night. The great temple and was no Great chunks of the  were embedded in the crater\u8217\'92s sloping walls. A great explosion which he had missed entirely.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Ayram, Pyetle, Moto and the others were there with him. They lolled their heads about, struggling to emerge from a similar sleep.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 All the demons were gone, as was the star which erased them. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No one will believe this,\u8221\'94 he said as he stared up at the sky.}}